"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Judges chapters 9–10
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-judges-9-10.py

Ch9: Abimelech's anti-kingdom — massacre of 70 brothers, Jotham's fable,
     three-year reign, ruin of Shechem and Thebez (57 verses)
Ch10: Minor judges (Tola, Jair), sevenfold apostasy, Ammonite oppression (18 verses)

Christological focus:
- Ch9: Abimelech as anti-type of the true king; Jotham's fable as parable of
  unworthy kingship; the 70 brothers as negative image of Israel's covenant
  community; millstone death as ironic reversal of power
- Ch10: YHWH's patient mercy through the apostasy cycle as the character behind
  the incarnation; 'his soul was impatient over the misery of Israel' as the
  divine compassion that drives redemption
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRIST = {
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>Abimelech goes to his mother's brothers in Shechem to build a political coalition. His claim — 'remember that I am your bone and your flesh' — is the covenant-kinship formula (Gen 2:23; 2 Sam 5:1) that binds families and tribes. Christ uses the same kinship logic in the opposite direction: he is not ashamed to call believers brothers (Heb 2:11), his solidarity based not on ethnic calculation but on shared humanity and shared sonship. Abimelech manipulates covenant language for political power; Christ fulfills it through self-giving.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Abimelech's proposal: which is better — seventy rulers or one? The seventy-or-one choice frames kingship as a utilitarian question rather than a covenantal one. The irony is that YHWH himself had said 'I will be your king' (8:23). The true answer to 'which is better — seventy or one' is: the One YHWH, the single divine King who rules justly. The NT applies this directly: there is one Lord, one faith, one baptism (Eph 4:5); one mediator between God and man, the man Christ Jesus (1 Tim 2:5).</p>",
    "3": "<p>Shechem's men are persuaded because <em>ʾāḥ</em> — 'he is our brother.' The appeal to brotherhood as the basis for political loyalty is a powerful but dangerous ground: it can justify tribalism and nepotism rather than justice. Christ redefines brotherhood: 'Whoever does the will of my Father in heaven is my brother and sister and mother' (Matt 12:50) — covenant obedience, not ethnic or kinship connection, is the true bond. Abimelech's manufactured brotherhood leads to mass fratricide; Christ's redeemed brotherhood is established by his own death for the family.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Seventy pieces of silver from the temple of Baal-berith — the king's coronation funded by the pagan god's treasury. <strong>Baal-berith</strong> ('lord of the covenant') represents a wholesale inversion of YHWH's covenantal relationship with Israel. Abimelech's rise is funded by a deity whose very name parodies YHWH. Christ was betrayed for thirty pieces of silver (Matt 26:15) — not from a pagan temple but from the Jerusalem treasury. The silver that funds the anti-king (Abimelech) and the silver that betrays the true King (Jesus) both serve as instruments of YHWH's ultimate purpose.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Abimelech kills <strong>seventy of his brothers on one stone</strong> — the number and the instrument. Seventy is the number of the Gentile nations (Gen 10) and the number of Jacob's descendants who went to Egypt (Gen 46:27); seventy elders governed Israel (Exod 24:1); Jesus sent out seventy-two (Luke 10:1). The killing of seventy represents the annihilation of legitimate covenantal community. <strong>On one stone</strong> (<em>ʾeben ʾaḥat</em>) — stone is the material of altars, memorials, and divine theophanies. The stone that kills the seventy stands in stark contrast to Christ, the living Stone who gives life to all who come to him (1 Pet 2:4).</p>",
    "6": "<p>All the leaders of Shechem and Beth-millo make Abimelech king by <strong>the oak of the pillar at Shechem</strong> (<em>ʾêlôn muṣṣāb ʾăšer biškem</em>). Shechem's sacred tree is the site of covenant ceremonies reaching back to Abraham (Gen 12:6) and Joshua's covenant renewal (Josh 24:26). The coronation of an illegitimate king at Israel's most venerable covenant site is a profound desecration. Jesus will enter Jerusalem to acclamation at a far greater covenant moment — but his 'coronation' leads not to power but to the cross, the ultimate covenant act.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Jotham's speech from Mount Gerizim — the mountain of covenant blessing (Deut 27:12). The surviving son of Gideon speaks the parable from the mountain of blessing while Abimelech reigns in the valley below. The parable's dramatic setting — one righteous witness against the assembled collaborators — anticipates the prophetic tradition of one lone voice against corporate moral failure. Jesus on a mountain (the Sermon on the Mount, Matt 5-7) speaks of the true nature of the Kingdom from the same posture: the mountaintop proclamation that challenges the prevailing social order below.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The parable begins: <strong>the trees go to anoint a king over them</strong> (<em>hālôk hāləkû hāʿēṣîm limšôaḥ ʿălêhem meleḵ</em>). The anointing vocabulary (<em>māšaḥ</em> H4886 — from which <em>māšîaḥ</em>, Messiah/Christ) applied to trees seeking a king is the parable's first irony. The legitimate anointing of Israel's king belongs to YHWH alone — Samuel anoints Saul and David by YHWH's command. When trees anoint their own king through popular demand rather than divine commission, the result is the bramble. Christ is anointed not by popular consensus but by the Father at his baptism: 'This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased' (Matt 3:17).</p>",
    "9": "<p>The olive tree refuses kingship: <strong>'Shall I leave my fatness, by which God and man are honored, and go to sway over the trees?'</strong> The olive's fatness (<em>dišnî</em> H1880) — its oil — is what honors God (priestly lamp-oil, Exod 27:20) and man (anointing oil, food, medicine). The olive's refusal is the right answer: the worthy tree understands its calling is not governance but fruitfulness. Christ is the true anointed one — the Messiah, whose very name means 'the anointed with oil.' He did not cling to equality with God as something to be exploited (Phil 2:6) but emptied himself. He who could rightly rule chose servanthood.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The fig tree is asked next. The fig is Israel's symbol of peace and prosperity (1 Kgs 4:25: everyone sat under their vine and fig tree in Solomon's peaceful reign). The fig tree's calling is sweetness and good fruit — the fruitfulness that Israel was meant to provide to the nations. Jesus cursed the unfruitful fig tree (Mark 11:12-14) as a sign-act of judgment on Israel's failure to bear the fruit of the Kingdom. The fig that refuses earthly kingship to remain fruitful represents the proper ordering of calling: the fruit of righteousness is more valuable than the power of rule.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The fig's refusal: <strong>'Shall I leave my sweetness and my good fruit and go to sway over the trees?'</strong> Both the olive and the fig recognize that their contribution to the community (oil, fruit) requires staying in place rather than rising to rule. This is the logic of servanthood that Christ embodies: the one who could legitimately rule over all things chose instead to serve. 'The Son of Man came not to be served but to serve, and to give his life as a ransom for many' (Mark 10:45). The worthy refuse the crown; the unworthy seize it.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The vine is asked. Wine (<em>tîrôš</em> H8492) gladdens God and man — a reference to the Nazirite offerings (Num 15:5-7: wine offerings accompany the peace offering) and the joy of covenant fellowship. Jesus explicitly connects himself to the vine: 'I am the true vine' (John 15:1). The parable's vine is asked to leave its calling to rule over other trees; Christ as the true vine does not abandon his fruitfulness for earthly rule — he extends it through his disciples who are branches (John 15:5). The vine's refusal to rule that it might bear fruit is the christological pattern of self-emptying service.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The vine refuses: <strong>'Shall I leave my wine that cheers God and man?'</strong> The 'cheering of God' (<em>məśammaḥ ʾĕlōhîm</em>) is unusual — the only other clear reference to something that 'cheers God' is the Noahic covenant's 'pleasing aroma' of sacrifice (Gen 8:21). Wine that cheers both God and man anticipates the Eucharistic cup: 'This cup is the new covenant in my blood. Do this, as often as you drink it, in remembrance of me' (1 Cor 11:25). The covenant cup that cheers is not established through earthly power but through Christ's voluntary sacrifice.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The bramble is finally asked: <strong>'You come and reign over us'</strong> — addressed to the tree that produces nothing, provides no shade, and only scratches and entangles. The bramble (<em>ʾāṭāḏ</em> H329, a thorny shrub) accepts eagerly what the worthy trees refused. The crown of thorns placed on Jesus's head at his crucifixion (Matt 27:29) may deliberately invoke this image: the thorny bramble/thorn crown is associated with curse (Gen 3:18: 'thorns and thistles'), and Jesus wears the bramble-crown of the cursed world to absorb its curse. The bramble kings of history are superseded by the one who wore the thornbush crown as a king of servants.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The bramble's condition: <strong>'If in truth you are anointing me as king, come and take refuge in my shade'</strong> — the bramble's 'shade' is an absurdity, since brambles provide no shade whatsoever. The bramble offers protection it cannot give: 'if not, let fire come out of the bramble and devour the cedars of Lebanon.' Fire from a bramble (<em>ʾēš</em> from <em>ʾāṭāḏ</em>) is the only realistic outcome when brambles burn: they ignite easily and burn intensely. Jesus warned against false leaders who promise shelter but cannot deliver: 'Can a blind man lead a blind man? Will they not both fall into a pit?' (Luke 6:39). The bramble king offers shelter; the true King offers rest (Matt 11:28).</p>",
    "16": "<p>Jotham's application: <strong>'Now therefore, if you acted in good faith and integrity when you made Abimelech king…'</strong> The parable's application hinges on the condition of good faith (<em>ʾemet</em> H571, truth/faithfulness) and integrity (<em>tāmîm</em> H8549, completeness/blamelessness). The covenant demand for integrity in leadership selection is YHWH's standard throughout the monarchy — Deuteronomy 17:14-20 specifies exactly what kind of king Israel may choose. Christ fulfills the Deuteronomic king-ideal perfectly: he is the king who does not multiply horses, wives, or gold, whose heart does not turn away, and who meditates on the Torah all his days (Deut 17:16-20).</p>",
    "17": "<p>Jotham's reminder: <strong>'My father fought for you, and risked his life, and rescued you from the hand of Midian'</strong> — Gideon's sacrifice for Israel. The pattern of a father who risked his life to rescue the people is the typological background for the Father who gave the Son: 'For God so loved the world that he gave his only Son' (John 3:16). Gideon's military self-risk points toward a greater self-giving. The ingratitude of Shechem toward Gideon's family (killing 70 sons) mirrors the ingratitude of those who reject the Son through whom the Father has acted.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The accusation: <strong>'You have risen against my father's house this day and have killed his sons, seventy men on one stone, and made Abimelech, the son of his slave woman, king over the men of Shechem.'</strong> The contrast between the legitimate seventy sons and the illegitimate one son of the slave woman is a reversal of the Sarah/Hagar pattern (Gen 21) — but inverted: here it is the slave's son who murders the free sons and seizes the inheritance. Paul uses the Hagar/Sarah typology to describe the contrast between law-covenant and grace-covenant (Gal 4:22-31). Abimelech's usurpation enacts the anti-pattern: the slave-born claiming dominion over the free.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Jotham's conditional: <strong>'If you have acted in good faith and integrity with Jerubbaal and with his house this day, then rejoice in Abimelech.'</strong> The ironic conditional — both speaker and audience know the condition has not been met — is a form of covenantal lawsuit. The prophetic form of the conditional accusation is used by Israel's prophets against covenant violation: 'if you had done X, then Y; since you did not, Z.' Jesus uses the same rhetorical form: 'If you were Abraham's children, you would be doing the works Abraham did' (John 8:39) — the conditional that exposes the gap between claimed identity and actual behavior.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The curse: <strong>'Let fire come out from Abimelech and devour the lords of Shechem and Beth-millo; and let fire come out from the lords of Shechem and devour Abimelech.'</strong> The mutual-destruction curse is fulfilled precisely in 9:49 and 9:53-54. Jotham's curse functions as prophetic oracle: the word spoken from the mountain of blessing becomes the word of judgment. Jesus similarly spoke words of judgment on Jerusalem that were precisely fulfilled in 70 CE (Luke 21:20-24). The prophet's word from the mountain outlasts the moment of its speaking and accomplishes its purpose in history.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Jotham flees to Beer (<em>bəʾēr</em> H876, 'well') and lives there in fear of Abimelech. The sole surviving righteous witness of a corrupt regime living in exile is an OT pattern (Elijah fleeing Jezebel, 1 Kgs 19:3; Jeremiah in the pit). Christ himself will flee to Egypt as an infant (Matt 2:13-14) — the righteous one preserved from a murderous ruler by flight. The righteous witness who cannot remain near power because power has become murderous is a recurring pattern that culminates in the flight from Herod's massacre and Christ's eventual voluntary return to Jerusalem for his death.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Abimelech ruled Israel <strong>three years</strong> (<em>šālōš šānîm</em>). The three-year reign is significant: it is the minimal duration that allows the narrative to establish Abimelech's regime as a real political fact before YHWH's judgment falls. Three years of oppressive rule before divine intervention mirrors other biblical timelines of divine patience followed by judgment. Christ's public ministry was also approximately three years — but his 'reign' begins at resurrection and extends forever, in direct contrast to the three-year pretender.</p>",
    "23": "<p><strong>God sent an evil spirit between Abimelech and the lords of Shechem</strong> (<em>wayyišlaḥ ʾĕlōhîm rûaḥ rāʿāh bên ʾăḇîmeleḵ ûḇên baʿălê šekem</em>). Divine use of a destructive spirit to accomplish judgment appears in 1 Sam 16:14 (an evil spirit torments Saul after YHWH's Spirit departs). The pattern is that YHWH's withdrawal of restraint allows destructive spiritual forces to accomplish his judicial purposes. The NT describes the same dynamic: God giving people over to their desires (Rom 1:24,26,28) as a form of judicial abandonment. The evil spirit between Abimelech and Shechem is YHWH's judicial instrument.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The divine purpose: <strong>that the violence done to the seventy sons might come, and their blood be laid on Abimelech their brother who killed them, and on the lords of Shechem who strengthened his hands</strong>. The principle of <em>lex talionis</em> at the divine level: those who shed innocent blood have their own blood required of them. This is the same principle behind the cross — the violence of the world against the innocent Son of God is required back from those who perpetrated it (Acts 2:23: 'this Jesus, delivered up according to the definite plan and foreknowledge of God, you crucified and killed by the hands of lawless men'). The innocent blood of the seventy cries out; the innocent blood of Christ speaks a better word (Heb 12:24).</p>",
    "25": "<p>The Shechemites' ambush of Abimelech on the mountain roads is the beginning of the civil conflict that will destroy both parties. The breakdown of trust between a tyrant and his collaborators is a recurring pattern: those who help illegitimate power gain authority eventually become threats to that authority. The collapse of the Abimelech-Shechem alliance is the working out of Jotham's curse — the mutual fire consuming both. Christ warned his disciples about the self-destructive nature of division: 'Every kingdom divided against itself is laid waste' (Matt 12:25).</p>",
    "26": "<p>Gaal son of Ebed arrives and gains the confidence of Shechem. His name <em>gaʿal</em> (H1603, possibly from <em>gāʾal</em> H1602, to abhor/loathe — or a separate root) and his patronymic <em>ben-ʿeḇeḏ</em> (son of the servant/slave) introduce a challenger from outside the existing power structure. False messiahs and pretend deliverers appear when legitimate leadership has failed — the Shechemites' embrace of Gaal mirrors the broader human pattern of trading one bad leader for another. Jesus warned about false Christs who would arise to lead astray if possible even the elect (Matt 24:24).</p>",
    "27": "<p>The Shechemites' harvest festival in the temple of their god — eating, drinking, cursing Abimelech. The harvest festival (<em>ḥag</em> H2282) in the Baal-berith temple is a religious celebration that doubles as political conspiracy. The alliance of religious practice with political rebellion is the chapter's recurring theme: Baal-berith ('Lord of the Covenant') is the deity who funds coups, hosts rebellion, and stores the silver of betrayal (v4). The parody of covenant practice in Baal-berith's temple stands against the true harvest festival of YHWH — a distinction Jesus draws when he cleanses the Jerusalem temple of those who have made it a 'den of robbers' (Matt 21:13).</p>",
    "28": "<p>Gaal's boast: <strong>'Who is Abimelech, and who is Shechem, that we should serve him? Is he not the son of Jerubbaal, and is not Zebul his officer?'</strong> The challenge to a ruling power by appealing to a purer identity claim (Shechem's original Canaanite heritage vs. Abimelech's Israelite father) is a form of identity politics. Gaal offers Shechem a pride-based alternative to submission. Jesus's authority challenge was the opposite: not 'who is Caesar that we should pay taxes?' but the deeper question of whose image is on the coin — and whose image is on the human soul (Matt 22:20-21). True authority is not argued by heritage but demonstrated by character and divine commission.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Gaal's empty boast: <strong>'Would that this people were under my hand! Then I would remove Abimelech.'</strong> The conditional wish for power — 'if only I ruled' — is the characteristic speech of those who do not yet have what they want but have no more righteousness than those they oppose. The would-be deliverer who boasts before any battle is fought has inverted the pattern of YHWH's genuine deliverers (Gideon who asks 'how shall I save Israel?' and Moses who objects 'Who am I?'). Christ makes no boast about what he would do if he had power — he is power, and he uses it to serve.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Zebul the governor's anger at Gaal's words and his secret message to Abimelech — loyalty to an illegitimate ruler maintained through political calculation. Zebul's report enables the counter-ambush. The chapter shows that Abimelech's regime depends entirely on informers, private intelligence, and military force rather than moral legitimacy or covenant faithfulness. The contrast with Christ's kingdom is complete: Jesus's kingdom requires no informers, no political calculation — it is established through truth spoken openly (John 18:20: 'I have spoken openly to the world').</p>",
    "31": "<p>Zebul sends to Abimelech secretly (<em>bātormāh</em> H8649 — with deception/secretly) — the communication is covert because the regime's security depends on deception rather than legitimate authority. Secret intelligence and covert operations characterize governments that rule by fear rather than consent. Christ's kingdom operates in the opposite register: what is whispered in secret shall be proclaimed on the housetops (Luke 12:3); the Kingdom of God advances through open proclamation rather than covert manipulation.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Abimelech is instructed to ambush the city at night — the night attack as military strategy mirrors the Judges pattern of surprise assault (Gideon at Jezreel, Samson at Gaza's gate). But where YHWH directed Gideon's night attack to deliver Israel, Abimelech's night attack is directed at Israelites — the same military pattern now in service of tyranny rather than liberation. The instruments of God's salvation can be appropriated by anti-redemptive powers; the form without the divine commission produces oppression rather than liberation.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Abimelech rises early in the morning to ambush Shechem — <em>babbōqer</em> (in the morning, at dawn). The dawn attack is the time when divine action often occurs in the OT (Exod 14:24: YHWH looks down at the Egyptian army in the morning watch; 2 Kgs 19:35: the angel strikes the Assyrian camp at night, and Israel finds them dead in the morning). Abimelech's dawn attack parodies the pattern of divine morning deliverance. Christ's resurrection occurs at dawn (Matt 28:1: 'toward the dawn of the first day of the week') — the true dawn attack that defeats the real enemy, death.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The four-company ambush around Shechem — the same numerical and tactical structure as Gideon's three-company night attack (7:16). Abimelech adapts the method of his father's greatest victory for use against Israelites. This is the typological tragedy of every generation: the instruments of redemption (tactics, structures, liturgies, leadership patterns) are inherited and applied to purposes the original deliverer never intended. The misuse of inherited spiritual tools for illegitimate ends is a NT warning: 'Not everyone who says to me, Lord, Lord, will enter the kingdom' (Matt 7:21).</p>",
    "35": "<p>Gaal goes out and stands at the entrance of the city gate — the gate being the political and judicial center of an ancient city (Ruth 4:1; Ps 127:5). Zebul draws him into battle. The gate-stand is a political and military statement: Gaal occupies the seat of authority. But his authority has no divine sanction and no genuine basis. The contrast with Christ who is the gate/door of the sheep (John 10:9: 'I am the door; if anyone enters by me, he will be saved') — the true entry-point of legitimate covenant community.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Gaal sees people coming down the mountains and Zebul deceives him: <strong>'You see the shadow of the mountains as men'</strong>. The moment of self-deception — seeing threats in shadows, dismissing real danger as optical illusion — characterizes those whose spiritual discernment is compromised by false confidence. The inability to accurately perceive reality is a judgment on those who have already rejected truth. Jesus's healing of the blind (John 9) is both physical and spiritual: he restores sight to those who cannot see themselves or their situation clearly.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Gaal's second sighting: <strong>'Look, people are coming down from the center of the land, and one company is coming from the direction of the Diviners' Oak'</strong>. The <em>Diviners' Oak</em> (<em>ʾêlôn məʿônənîm</em> H5772) — a tree associated with pagan divination, the antithesis of seeking YHWH at his sanctuary. The battle forms near a divination site: the chapter consistently associates Abimelech's power with Canaanite religious infrastructure (Baal-berith, the Diviners' Oak). Legitimate kingship in Israel was to be grounded in Torah-meditation and YHWH's counsel (Deut 17:18-19); Abimelech's kingdom is surrounded by the paraphernalia of false spiritual guidance.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Zebul's scathing rebuke: <strong>'Where is your mouth now, you who said: Who is Abimelech, that we should serve him? Are not these the people you despised? Go out now and fight them.'</strong> The collapse of boastful confidence before actual threat is the narrative's ironic justice: Gaal who spoke with contempt of Abimelech must now face him. Proverbs 16:18: 'Pride goes before destruction, and a haughty spirit before a fall.' Christ reverses the dynamic: he who had every right to boast emptied himself (Phil 2:7), so that those who boast in the cross (Gal 6:14) boast in a righteousness not their own.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Gaal goes out and fights Abimelech — and is routed. The sequence is complete: false boast → real battle → real defeat. The pattern of the would-be deliverer who lacks YHWH's commission ending in defeat is repeated throughout Judges (no judge-deliverer wins unless YHWH explicitly commissions and empowers). Gaal has neither YHWH's commission nor Jotham's prophetic standing — he is simply a political opportunist exploiting Shechem's discontent. The genuine deliverer, by contrast, is always reluctant, always divinely commissioned, and never boastful before battle.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Abimelech pursues Gaal to the city gate, and many fall wounded. The gate that Gaal occupied as his seat of authority is now the boundary of his defeat — he barely retreats inside it. The gate as a boundary between safety and destruction appears throughout Scripture: Noah's ark, the Passover doorpost, the city of refuge. The gate functions as a last mercy: Gaal escapes inside it. Christ is the gate (John 10:9) — those who enter through him find salvation; those outside face judgment. The gate that saves is also the boundary that judges.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Abimelech stays at Arumah, and Zebul drives out Gaal and his brothers from Shechem. The expulsion of the rebel from the city — driven out rather than killed — is a form of political exile. Expulsion from the covenant community (excommunication) has its NT parallel in the church's disciplinary practice (Matt 18:17; 1 Cor 5:13). The driving out is Zebul's act of loyalty to the regime — demonstrating that political loyalty, like covenant faithfulness, involves action, not merely verbal assent.</p>",
    "42": "<p>The people of Shechem go out into the fields the next day — resuming normal agricultural life as if political crisis were resolved. Abimelech is told and sends three companies to ambush them. The return to agricultural normality after a political crisis is a form of moral numbness: the people have witnessed the failed coup and assume the danger has passed. Jesus warned against exactly this: 'As were the days of Noah, so will be the coming of the Son of Man. For as in those days before the flood they were eating and drinking... until the day Noah entered the ark' (Matt 24:37-38). Normal life resumed is not safety secured.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Abimelech divides his men into three companies and hides in the field — again the three-company ambush that echoes Gideon's tactics. The fields where the Shechemites go to work become the killing ground. Agricultural work, which in YHWH's economy is a blessing (Gen 1:28-29; 2:15), is here turned into a trap. The corruption of created goods — land, work, harvest — by violence is the consequence of covenant failure. The restoration of the land's goodness is a messianic promise (Isa 65:21-22: 'they shall plant vineyards and eat their fruit... my chosen ones shall long enjoy the work of their hands').</p>",
    "44": "<p>Abimelech rushes forward and takes his stand at the entrance of the city gate while two companies pursue and strike those in the fields. The coordinated assault — cutting off escape at the gate while destroying those in the field — is total tactical encirclement. The chapter has moved from Jotham's prophetic parable to political conspiracy to open warfare to massacre — the progressive unveiling of tyranny's nature. Jesus's parable of the wicked tenants who kill the vineyard owner's servants and ultimately the son (Matt 21:33-44) follows a similar escalation pattern.</p>",
    "45": "<p>Abimelech fights against the city all day, takes it, kills the people, tears down the city, and <strong>sows it with salt</strong> (<em>wayyizrāʿehā meleḥ</em>). Salting a conquered city was an ANE ritual of permanent destruction and imprecation — salt sterilizes the ground, preventing regrowth. The salting of Shechem is an act of covenant curse: the city that chose the bramble king over YHWH's covenant is made permanently barren. Jesus wept over Jerusalem (Luke 19:41-44) before pronouncing its coming desolation — the divine sorrow before judgment that distinguishes YHWH's character from Abimelech's cold calculation.</p>",
    "46": "<p>The leaders of Shechem's tower enter the stronghold of the temple of El-berith (<em>bêt-ʾēl bərît</em> — 'house of El of the Covenant,' a variant name for Baal-berith). The final refuge of Shechem's leaders is their temple: when all political and military options fail, the oppressed turn to their god. The theology of the chapter is that false gods cannot protect: the bramble king's fire devours the very temple that funded him. God alone is refuge and strength, a very present help in trouble (Ps 46:1) — but only the true God, not the parodic 'Lord of the Covenant' who has no power to save.</p>",
    "47": "<p>Abimelech is told that all the leaders of the tower of Shechem have gathered together. The intelligence report reaches Abimelech immediately — his surveillance network is efficient even in the final stages of his campaign against his own people. The tyrant who requires total information control (knowing where everyone is and gathering them for destruction) is the anti-shepherd. Christ as the Good Shepherd knows his own sheep individually (John 10:14) — not to destroy but to protect and give abundant life.</p>",
    "48": "<p>Abimelech goes to <strong>Mount Zalmon</strong> and cuts down a bundle of brushwood, puts it on his shoulder, and commands his men to do the same. The personal participation of the king in the brutal task — cutting wood for burning — demonstrates the intensity of his vengeance. The wood-carrying image has a christological resonance: Jesus carried his own cross to Golgotha (John 19:17). But where Abimelech carries wood to burn others, Christ carries his cross to be burned (consumed) on behalf of others. The same physical act, the same burden — completely opposite purposes.</p>",
    "49": "<p>About <strong>1,000 people die</strong> when the tower of Shechem is burned — men and women who had taken refuge in the sacred stronghold. The burning of a sacred refuge, killing all who sought shelter there, is the destruction of the last possible sanctuary. The temple of Baal-berith that funded Abimelech (v4) and sheltered his collaborators is burned by its own creation. The principle that idols cannot protect is demonstrated materially: the god's house and the god's people are destroyed together. Christ is the sanctuary that does not fail (Rev 21:22: the Lord God Almighty and the Lamb are its temple).</p>",
    "50": "<p>Abimelech goes to Thebez, besieges it, and takes it. Thebez (<em>tēḇēṣ</em> H8405, possibly 'brightness') is identified with modern Tubas, north of the Jezreel Valley. The campaign has extended from Shechem to Thebez — the conquest is expanding rather than concluding. Tyranny is by nature expansionist: each conquest generates the need for another to maintain dominance. The contrast with Christ's kingdom, which grows not through conquest but through invitation (Matt 11:28-29: 'Come to me... I am gentle and lowly in heart'), could not be sharper.</p>",
    "51": "<p>All the men, women, and leaders of Thebez flee into the strong tower (<em>migdal-ʿōz</em> H4026 H5797) — a fortified refuge in the center of the city. Tower-as-refuge is a biblical metaphor for divine protection: YHWH is a strong tower to which the righteous run (Prov 18:10). Here the physical tower does what the spiritual metaphor promises: it protects those who flee inside. The specific detail that women are among those who flee into the tower sets up v53 — the woman who kills the attacker. Even in the darkest chapter of Judges' appendix, YHWH preserves a remnant through unexpected means.</p>",
    "52": "<p>Abimelech comes up to the tower door to set it on fire — completing the pattern of the Shechem tower (v49). The second tower-burning follows the first exactly, suggesting Abimelech's method has become habit. Repeating the same tactic that succeeded at Shechem at Thebez is the military assumption that past success predicts future outcome. But YHWH's interventions are not predictable from past patterns: the cross itself is the greatest historical reversal of expectation. What works against Shechem's tower will not work at Thebez's tower — YHWH has arranged otherwise.</p>",
    "53": "<p>A woman drops an upper millstone on Abimelech's head, crushing his skull. The <strong>upper millstone</strong> (<em>peleḵ reḵeḇ</em> H6400 H7393) — the hand-operated upper millstone of a grain mill, dropped from height — is the weapon of an anonymous woman. The millstone crushing a head is a death image that reverses the Genesis 3:15 promise: 'he shall bruise your head.' But here it is not the Seed of the woman but the woman herself who crushes the head of the tyrant. The instrument of grain-grinding (daily domestic labor) becomes the instrument of justice. Deborah and Jael; the woman of Thebez — women as unexpected instruments of YHWH's deliverance are a Judges pattern pointing toward the greatest unexpected instrument: the Virgin's son.</p>",
    "54": "<p>Abimelech's last words: <strong>'Draw your sword and kill me, lest it be said of me, a woman killed him'</strong> — the final irony. The king who lived by violence and male military power cannot accept death by a woman's hand as the end of his story. He requests his own armored-bearer to kill him, preferring death by sword to the shame of the millstone. The obsession with honor in death is the opposite of Christ's bearing of shame: Jesus 'endured the cross, despising the shame' (Heb 12:2). The true King accepted the ultimate dishonor; the false king could not bear a minor one. The armor-bearer runs him through — and the shame attaches anyway: the NT and later tradition remember the woman of Thebez.</p>",
    "55": "<p>When Israel sees that Abimelech is dead, everyone goes home — the sudden dispersal after the tyrant's death. There is no celebration, no leader to fill the vacuum, no theological reflection in the narrative — just dispersal. The brevity is itself a judgment: Abimelech's three-year reign ends not with lamentation or triumph but with people going home. The contrast with the responses to genuine judges' deaths (Gideon mourned and buried in v32; the land resting under Othniel, Deborah, and others) is complete: no one mourns Abimelech; no peace follows his death.</p>",
    "56": "<p>The narrator's theological verdict: <strong>God repaid Abimelech for the evil he did to his father in killing his seventy brothers</strong>. The divine repayment (<em>yāšaḇ</em> H7725, to return/restore — 'God returned upon Abimelech') is the principle of exact retributive justice. The same principle governs the cross from the human side: the evil done to the innocent Son of God will be repaid to those who perpetrate it. But the cross uniquely inverts it from Christ's side: Christ absorbs the divine retribution against human evil rather than returning it. 'He who knew no sin was made sin for us' (2 Cor 5:21) — bearing our repayment so we might receive his righteousness.</p>",
    "57": "<p>All the evil of the men of Shechem returned on their own heads — Jotham's curse fulfilled. The fulfillment of the prophetic word spoken from Mount Gerizim is the chapter's closing affirmation: YHWH's word does not return empty (Isa 55:11). Jotham the sole surviving witness spoke truth; the truth he spoke came to pass. The NT pattern of prophetic fulfillment follows the same structure: the prophets spoke; history fulfilled. 'All this took place to fulfill what the Lord had spoken by the prophet' (Matt 1:22) — but where Jotham's word brought destruction, the prophets' words about Christ bring salvation.</p>"
  },
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>Tola son of Puah, of the tribe of Issachar, arises to save Israel after Abimelech. <em>qûm</em> (H6965, to arise/rise up) — the technical term for YHWH raising up a deliverer (2:16,18). Tola (<em>tôlāʿ</em> H8439, crimson-worm/scarlet grub) — the name is associated with the scarlet dye produced from the <em>tola</em> worm, used in the tabernacle (Exod 25:4) and in purification rituals (Lev 14:4). The scarlet worm as a deliverance name has been read typologically: Psalm 22:6 — 'I am a worm and not a man' — the psalmist's self-description in the crucifixion psalm. Tola the scarlet-worm judge arises after Abimelech's chaos to restore order, as the Scarlet-wounded Christ rises to restore the broken covenant.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Tola judges Israel <strong>twenty-three years</strong> and is buried in Shamir. His judgeship is the longest consecutive period of peace in the post-Gideon era, yet the narrator gives him only two verses. YHWH's ordinary providential government of history — the faithful leaders who maintain covenant order for decades — receives less narrative attention than the spectacular deliverances and catastrophic failures. The quiet twenty-three years of Tola's judgeship are not less important than Gideon's dramatic defeat of Midian; they are simply less cinematically compelling. The incarnation came in an unremarkable Roman province in a quiet village — not into a spectacular moment.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Jair the Gileadite arises and judges Israel twenty-two years. Jair (<em>yāʾîr</em> H2971, possibly 'he enlightens' or 'YHWH enlightens') — a name associated with the Gileadite family of Manasseh (Num 32:41; Deut 3:14). The Gileadite judges (Jair here; Jephthah in ch11-12) represent the Transjordanian tribal territory, east of the Jordan, which will face the Ammonite threat directly. Minor judges like Tola and Jair provide continuity between the major judge-narratives — they are the hidden backbone of Israel's covenant governance, unnamed in Hebrews 11 but preserved in God's record.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Jair's <strong>thirty sons who rode on thirty donkeys</strong> and held <strong>thirty cities</strong> called Havvoth-jair. The parallel structure — thirty sons, thirty donkeys, thirty cities — is a sign of prosperity, tribal stability, and effective regional governance. The donkey as a riding animal is significant: it is the mount of peaceful rulers (Zech 9:9: 'your king comes to you, humble and mounted on a donkey'), not of war (horses). Jair's sons riding donkeys suggests a peaceable regional administration — an image of the kingdom's shalom that anticipates the messianic king who enters Jerusalem on a donkey to proclaim peace.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Jair dies and is buried in Kamon. The minor judges' epitaphs — bare names, brief service durations, burial places — are the OT's version of the 'cloud of witnesses' (Heb 12:1): faithful servants whose stories are compressed to essentials because they point beyond themselves to something greater. The burial at Kamon is the final word on Jair: he served, he died, he was buried. This is the trajectory of every judge — they rise, deliver (or maintain), die. The resurrection reverses the trajectory: Christ rose, will never die again, and his death was the death of death (1 Cor 15:26).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The seventh and most comprehensive apostasy list: <strong>Israel did what was evil, serving the Baals and the Ashtaroth, and the gods of Syria, Sidon, Moab, Ammon, and the Philistines. They forsook YHWH and did not serve him.</strong> The enumeration of seven divine objects — Baals, Ashtaroth, Syria, Sidon, Moab, Ammon, Philistia — is the most comprehensive list of Israel's idolatry in Judges. Seven is the number of completeness: Israel has comprehensively transferred their covenant loyalty to every available alternative. The NT counterpart is Paul's list of sins that exclude from the kingdom (1 Cor 6:9-10) and the world's systematic rejection of Christ (John 1:10-11).</p>",
    "7": "<p>YHWH's anger burns against Israel and he sells them into the hand of the <strong>Philistines and Ammonites</strong>. <em>mākar</em> (H4376, to sell/give into the power of) — the same verb as Joseph being sold by his brothers (Gen 37:28). YHWH 'sells' Israel into bondage as a judicial act: they chose other masters, so YHWH gives them over to those masters. The double oppressor — Philistines and Ammonites on two fronts simultaneously — is the most severe external pressure since the opening of Judges. The compounding of judgment corresponds to the compounding of apostasy: comprehensive idolatry produces comprehensive oppression.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Ammonites <strong>crushed and oppressed the people of Israel for eighteen years</strong> — the oppression is both intensive ('crushed') and extensive (eighteen years). <em>rāṣaṣ</em> (H7533, to crush/break/oppress) and <em>ʿāṣar</em> (H6231, to oppress/vex) — double verbs for the severity. The eighteen years of Ammonite oppression in Transjordan plus the forty years of Philistine oppression (13:1) represents the longest sustained foreign domination in Judges. The duration of oppression calibrates to the severity of the apostasy: the more comprehensive the covenant violation, the longer the covenant consequences.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The Ammonites cross the Jordan to fight Judah, Benjamin, and Ephraim — the oppression spreads from Transjordan into Cisjordan. The expansion of the threat to include the central tribes (Judah, Benjamin, Ephraim) is the escalation that drives the next cry for help. Israel is greatly distressed (<em>wayyēṣer liyiśrāʾēl məʾōḏ</em> — 'and it was very distressing to Israel'). The pattern of distress driving prayer is not accidental: suffering that produces genuine repentance fulfills YHWH's disciplinary purpose. The cross produces the same dynamic: the depth of Christ's suffering reveals the depth of human sin and drives genuine contrition.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Israel cries out to YHWH: <strong>'We have sinned against you, because we have forsaken our God and have served the Baals.'</strong> The confession is specific and accurate: they name the actual sin (forsaking YHWH, serving Baals) rather than just crying out for help. This is the first clearly articulated confession of sin in Judges — previous cries were more expressions of distress than confessions. The specificity of the confession is important in both Testaments: genuine repentance names the sin, not merely the suffering. 'If we confess our sins, he is faithful and just to forgive us our sins and to cleanse us from all unrighteousness' (1 John 1:9).</p>",
    "11": "<p>YHWH's response — not immediately comfort but a recital of past deliverances: <strong>'Did I not save you from the Egyptians and from the Amorites... the Ammonites... the Philistines?'</strong> The divine cross-examination recalls YHWH's saving history to expose the ingratitude. The Exodus (Egypt), the Amorite wars (Joshua), previous Ammonite and Philistine deliverances — the full span of YHWH's saving acts is listed. This is the pattern of the covenant lawsuit (<em>rîb</em>): YHWH rehearses his faithfulness as the standard against which Israel's unfaithfulness is measured. The NT applies the same logic in the parable of the unmerciful servant (Matt 18:23-35): the one who has been forgiven much is expected to forgive much.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The additional deliverances: <strong>Sidonians, Amalek, Maon</strong> — oppressors not otherwise mentioned in the Judges narrative, suggesting a wider history of divine rescue than the text explicitly narrates. The breadth of YHWH's past saving acts makes the present apostasy more inexcusable, not less. The accumulated weight of divine faithfulness is also the basis of NT assurance: 'He who did not spare his own Son but gave him up for us all, how will he not also with him graciously give us all things?' (Rom 8:32). The God who delivered through all those crises will deliver through the final crisis.</p>",
    "13": "<p>YHWH's declaration: <strong>'Yet you have forsaken me and served other gods; therefore I will save you no more.'</strong> The divine refusal to save — <em>lōʾ-ʾôsîp ləhôšîaʿ ʾetkem</em> — is the most extreme statement of covenantal withdrawal in Judges. The refusal is conditional and serves a disciplinary purpose: it forces Israel to confront the seriousness of their covenant violation. YHWH does not ultimately abandon Israel (the deliverer will come in ch11), but the declaration of withdrawal creates the crisis that drives genuine repentance. Jesus uses the same pattern: the parable of the prodigal's father does not pursue the son — he allows the crisis to deepen until the son 'comes to himself' (Luke 15:17).</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>'Go and cry out to the gods whom you have chosen; let them save you in the time of your distress.'</strong> The divine irony is devastating: if Israel has chosen other gods, let them experience those gods' actual saving ability. The challenge to the false gods — go to them for help — is the same challenge YHWH issues through Isaiah 41:21-24 (present your case, prove your predictions, do something, good or ill). False gods cannot save; their impotence is proven precisely at the moment when salvation is most needed. The idols that seemed attractive in prosperity prove worthless in distress — which is why Christ's value is demonstrated most clearly in the crucible of suffering.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Israel's response to YHWH's refusal: <strong>'We have sinned; do to us whatever seems good to you. Only please deliver us this day.'</strong> The surrender — 'do to us whatever seems good' (<em>kaṭṭôḇ bəʿênêkā ʿăśēh-lānû</em>) — is the opposite of the book's recurring 'what is right in his own eyes.' Israel submits their fate to YHWH's judgment rather than their own evaluation. This is the posture of genuine repentance and the opposite of the autonomous self-rule that characterized the entire book. Jesus's Gethsemane prayer echoes this exactly: 'Not my will, but yours, be done' (Luke 22:42) — total submission of will to the Father at the moment of greatest distress.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>They put away the foreign gods and served YHWH, and he became impatient over the misery of Israel</strong> (<em>wattiqṣar napšô baʿămal yiśrāʾēl</em>). The phrase <em>qāṣar nepeš</em> — 'his soul was shortened/impatient' — is the same idiom used of Samson (16:16) where it means reaching one's limit of endurance; applied to YHWH, it means his compassion was so moved by Israel's suffering that he could no longer refrain from acting. This is the interior of the divine character that drives all redemptive action: YHWH cannot bear to watch his people's misery indefinitely. The incarnation is the ultimate expression of this: 'God so loved the world that he gave' (John 3:16) — the divine impatience with human misery that moved heaven to send the Son.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The Ammonites encamp in Gilead, and Israel assembles at Mizpah. The geographic setting returns to Transjordan: Gilead and Mizpah are the staging ground for the next judge, Jephthah. The assembly at Mizpah mirrors the assembly at Mizpah in ch20-21, but with a different outcome: here Israel gathers for defensive war against an external enemy rather than internal civil conflict. The gathering at Mizpah as a crisis-response assembly will recur in Samuel's era (1 Sam 7:5-12) — it becomes a symbol of national repentance-and-mobilization. The assembly of the church under persecution mirrors this pattern: crisis drives the community to gather, pray, and seek divine direction.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The leaders of Gilead declare: <strong>'Who is the man who will begin to fight against the Ammonites? He shall be head over all the inhabitants of Gilead.'</strong> The offer of leadership in exchange for military service introduces the Jephthah situation — a negotiated rather than divinely commissioned judge. The conditional kingship offer ('whoever fights, gets to rule') inverts the divine appointment pattern: previous judges were raised by YHWH and then served. Jephthah will negotiate his way into authority — a problematic basis for a deliverer whose tragic flaw (the rash vow) has much to do with his insecure social position. Christ's authority is not negotiated: 'All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me' (Matt 28:18) — given by the Father, not bargained from a crisis.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'judges')
    merge_comm(c, CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'judges', c)
    print(f'judges mkt-christ: wrote {sum(len(v) for v in CHRIST.values())} verses across ch 9-10')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
